It's a fantastic video, but if an italian can tell you a tip:
In the original Carbonara, you need to separate the yolk from the glair.
You need to use only the yolk.

Another tip for the quantity of yolk:

Use a base of 2 yolk, plus 1 yolk for person.

In the original Carbonara, you need to separate the yolk from the glair.

Use a base of 2 yolk, plus 1 yolk for person.

(English ) With all due respect to antonio but there are mistakes. Extra virgin olive oil is not used. Fundamental is pecorino and pepper. The pasta need to be mixes in another bowl cold, not in the pan. The yellow part of guanciale should be removed because it is rancid.

(Italiano) Con tutto il rispetto per antonio ma ci sono degli errori. Non si usa l olio extra vergine. Fondamentale e' il pecorino e pepe. La pasta si mescola in un altra bowl ,no nella padella. Dal guanciale si toglie la parte gialla perche rancida.
textOriginal:
(English ) With all due respect to antonio but there are mistakes.  Extra virgin olive oil is not used. Fundamental is pecorino and pepper.  The pasta need to be  mixes in another bowl cold, not in the pan.  The yellow part of guanciale should be  removed  because it is rancid.

(Italiano) Con tutto il rispetto per antonio ma ci sono degli errori. Non si usa l olio extra vergine. Fondamentale e' il pecorino e pepe. La pasta si mescola in un altra bowl ,no nella padella. Dal guanciale si toglie la parte gialla perche rancida.

textDisplay:
- 220g Spaghetti or Spaghettoni (the largest spaghetti)
- 25g Guanciale (the cheek of the pork) or pancetta (Italian bacon) cut into small cubes.
- 2 tbsp olive oil
- 2 eggs
- 50g Parmesan cheese (or aged pecorino) freshly grated.
- Freshly ground black pepper.
textOriginal:
- 220g Spaghetti or Spaghettoni (the largest spaghetti)
- 25g Guanciale (the cheek of the pork) or pancetta (Italian bacon) cut into small cubes.
- 2 tbsp olive oil
- 2 eggs
- 50g Parmesan cheese (or aged pecorino) freshly grated.
- Freshly ground black pepper.

textDisplay:
I'll give you a lesson in the history of Italian cuisine.
Carbonara, like Amatriciana are variants of Gricia pasta.
Gricia pasta = Pasta + Guanciale + Pecorino.
This is because they are dishes that shepherds cooked in the mountains 100 years ago. The ingredients are what you could bring along, seasoned bacon and seasoned cheese, and of course pasta (actually flour, with which they made pasta). All things that could be kept for a long time. Guanciale was used instead of oil, which could not be brought to the mountains. So, the only wrong thing is to put olive oil to cook the Guanciale. If you then have to use the napkin to remove it, it is useless to put it on.
When they came down from the mountains and returned to their home, they could also put other ingredients such as eggs and tomatoes.
Carbonara = Gricia + Eggs
Amatriciana = Gricia + Tomato
True Romans do not put oil in any of these 3 recipes, indeed it is a mortal sin.
However, it is the recipe that comes closest to the real one. Do not put the oil and you will have made the real carbonara.

p.s. I'm Italian, although I wrote in English.

textDisplay:
This is not an original recipe...sorry to be the devils advocate, but it’s not. The ingredients are original but the procedures are not correct. In the original, or ancient recipe, you whipped the eggs whites by them selfs, the incorporeal with the egg yolk/cheese/black pepper mix to create a foamy mixture; incorporate with a whisk from bottom to up, to create a circle, slowly without braking the air into the white eggs. And you do not mix the pasta with the mix in the same pan you cooked the guanciale. You sauté the spaghetti in the pan and than you place the pasta in a room temperature ceramic or glass or stainless steel bowl and than you add the egg mix. You mix it in there so the egg mixture will not overcooked. Do no use plastic bowl because the eggs will melt like liquid. Now you have the original carbonara. Ciao belli e cucinate bene, così mangiate meglio.
Alessandro Serni.

textDisplay:
Io scrivo dall'Italia. Anche la tua esecuzione non è perfetta. Ci sono alcune cose da correggere e alcuni piccoli errori che fanno diventare un buon piatto in un eccellente piatto. Ma devo dire che rispetto agli altri americani che imitano i piatti italiani in un modo "schifoso" il tuo e molto ma molto meglio. Nessuno riesce a fare ne la carbonara ne altre specialità come le facciamo noi italiani ma se almeno le eseguissero come hai fatto tu già sarebbe una bella cosa..
P.s. Metti poco olio all'inizio e fai sciogliere il guanciale a bassa temperatura. Quando ha rilasiato il suo grasso togli il guanciale dall'olio e mettilo da una parte per farlo rimanere croccante. ... lo metterai alla fine un po nella padella assieme alla pasta e un poco sopra alla pasta nei piatti per guarnizione. Impara a salatare la pasta specialmente quando metti le uova. La cosa più importante: si devono usare solo i tuorli, niente albume. Per due perone 3 uova, per quattro persone 5 uova. Le uova quando le sbatti metti un pod'acqua per renderle più fredde. Perchè nella padella non devono superare i 55 gradi altrimenti si creano dei grumi. Quando le salti deve essere come una crema che avvolge gli spaghetti. Ti metto il like perchè tra gli americani sei stato il migliore.

textDisplay: @Michel A jamie Oliver non scivo, perchè non lo considero proprio, noi in Italia  i suoi video li usiamo per farci un sacco di risate. A te dico:  Si può conoscere l'inglese e rimanere un asino. Io non ne ho bisogno, ma in ogni caso conosco il giusto che mi serve per il mio lavoro.  O credi che conoscere l'inglese ti renda uno chef?.  Ogni cosa che scrivi  dimostra la tua ignoranza. Sei proprio un cretino!  Ti faccio un piccolo spoiler anch'io: Sono un medico, mi intendo e ho studiato da chef solo per mio diletto e  per mia passione. Perciò prima di parlare di lipidi, glucidi,  proteine e quant'altro con me, dovresti prima fare 6 anni di università come li ho fatti io. Vorrei veramente che esistesse il patentino da ufo, cosi te ne andresti fuori dal mondo conosciuto,  senza rompere le scatole a chi  è impegnato in cose più importanti. Per rispondere a uno che scrive in dialetto, non c'era bisogno di mettere tutte le virgole, perchè magari le avresti scambiate per dei geroglifici.  Inoltre non devo mostrare attestati a un signor "nessuno" come te.  La mia è pura passione ed è per questo che si anela sempre alla perfezione. E ti ripeto, certe regole in cucina non sono in discussione, si fa così e basta. Poi ognuno a casa sua, può mangiare tutte le schifezze che vuole, ma non può dettare legge agli italiani, sulle ricette tradizionali italiane.  Ti consiglio, per la prossima volta di scrivere tutto in una volta e non in 2 trance, perchè da noi in Italia c'è un detto, che dice: solo i cornuti ci ripensano.....  Mi dispiacerebbe pensare anche questo di te.  E con questo ho chiuso con te, mi hai preso già troppo tempo.  C'è un altro detto, che dice: A lavar la testa all'asino, si perde tempo e sapone.... Addio

textDisplay: I have never seen scrambled eggs plopped onto a slice of toast in America before and I've been cooking breakfast in restaurants for my whole life.  If anything perhaps the toast goes on top of the eggs sometimes but not under.  That's how you get soggy toast.  If I put eggs on toast like that my guests would send it back and complain that their toast is soggy.  Don't need milk or cream if you cook them right?   Milk/cream is essential to the flavor of scrambled eggs.  I use milk some use cream but eggs don't taste right without it.  You can't get that flavor without milk regardless of how right you're cooking it.

textDisplay:
"So how do you cook your eggs? Let us know!"
Scramble the whites, whichever texture you most feel like, then put the still-intact yolks on top and steam juuuust enough to make them into warm golden syrup bubbles which, when popped, ooze all over other foods. "Scrambles, runny side up." Serve on a giant slice of sourdough with a generous glop of chili sauce, or on a bowl of rice with a generous helping of kimchee.
textOriginal:
"So how do you cook your eggs?  Let us know!"  
Scramble the whites, whichever texture you most feel like, then put the still-intact yolks on top and steam juuuust enough to make them into warm golden syrup bubbles which, when popped, ooze all over other foods.  "Scrambles, runny side up."  Serve on a giant slice of sourdough with a generous glop of chili sauce, or on a bowl of rice with a generous helping of kimchee.

textDisplay:
I don’t understand all these objections to using olive oil or lemon on the steak. I’ve been cooking steak this way for years which is why I am known as the king of steak in my family. The only thing I do different is that I actually marinate my steaks in lemon, olive oil, and salt before I cook them, sometimes for as much as 24 hours.
The lemon tenderizes the meat. I don’t use pepper because I find it tends to burn leaving an acrid taste.
textOriginal:

The only thing I do different is that I actually marinate my steaks in lemon, olive oil, and salt before I cook them, sometimes for as much as 24 hours. 
The lemon tenderizes the meat. I don’t use pepper because I find it tends to burn leaving an acrid taste.

textDisplay:
martino doni Listen here, you moron.
I just watched the video in which three Italian chefs went over this video. Let’s see...
- They never insulted Gennaro in any way or even made fun of him. They were just amused about his behavior on camera.
- They never specifically said anything he did was inherently wrong. Only how it differs from the traditional Neapolitan way. And by the way- Never did Gennaro claim in this video that the pizza he’s making is "real" or "authentic". It was all about showing an easy recipe.
Now for all of the things the three chefs pointed out:
- Mixing a non-gramm-based amount of Salt with flour is unusual.
- Neapolitan pizza rests for 7-8 hours minimum instead of 2 like Gennaro’s.
- Traditionally, you would use Pecorino instead of Parmesan, but a mixture of the two is also possible.
- The Mozzarella should be cut up and chilled before being used instead of freshly torn.
Lastly, after dozens of people asking you for a recipe because of you claiming you could give one, you still haven’t provided anything.

This video is the business and I'm definitely going to make my own bases - thin and crispy the Italian way is by far the best.

textDisplay:
I just made this pizza and it is absolutely the BEST.
Medium size is 1/2 amount
250g bread flour
1/2 tsp salt
3.5g fresh yeast
163ml warm water
1/4 to 1/2 tsp sugar - to activate yeast and flavor :)

I allowed to rise for 1 1/2 hours covered with a towel in oven, with a bowl of hot water for moisture and warmth
Then I spread the crust into a square and olive oil all over the top of it
Then I used my favorite tomatoes for the sauce, which is Dei Fratelli Stewed Tomatoes and I added sugar to this (I can't stand acidic stuff, so I just had a little-bit of sweetness)
Then I sprinkled the Parmesan cheese, as he recommended and placed chunks of the fresh buffalo mozzarella and placed a fresh leaf of basil for each piece
Then I baked it at 400 F for 10 minutes.

Fantastic!!! Truly FANTASTIC!!
I will definitely make this again, and for others!
textOriginal:
I just made this pizza and it is absolutely the BEST.
Medium size is 1/2 amount
250g bread flour
1/2 tsp salt
3.5g fresh yeast
163ml warm water
1/4 to 1/2 tsp sugar - to activate yeast and flavor :)

I allowed to rise for 1 1/2 hours covered with a towel in oven, with a bowl of hot water for moisture and warmth 
Then I spread the crust into a square and olive oil all over the top of it
Then I used my favorite tomatoes for the sauce, which is Dei Fratelli Stewed Tomatoes and I added sugar to this (I can't stand acidic stuff, so I just had a little-bit of sweetness)
Then I sprinkled the Parmesan cheese, as he recommended and placed chunks of the fresh buffalo mozzarella and placed a fresh leaf of basil for each piece
Then I baked it at 400 F for 10 minutes.

Fantastic!!! Truly FANTASTIC!!
I will definitely make this again, and for others!

textDisplay:
We were attending Dinner the other day and a friend of my dad came over so we went to a local Restaurant. We ordered Carbonara for 40 Bucks per dish, the taste was like.. out of the world good.. Explains the pricetag, i assume?
I was curious and asked the waiter to get me the Cook so i can ask him what he used to make the dish.
I didn't think that he would give all of it away and, of course, he didn't, but he just laughed and told me:
"Don't use bacon from tha' pork, use Bresaola"
If you are looking for the "perfect" carbonara and you'd like to test out something new, why not testing this?
Have a good day :)
textOriginal:
We were attending Dinner the other day and a friend of my dad came over so we went to a local Restaurant. We ordered Carbonara for 40 Bucks per dish, the taste was like.. out of the world good.. Explains the pricetag, i assume? 
I was curious and asked the waiter to get me the Cook so i can ask him what he used to make the dish.
I didn't think that he would give all of it away and, of course, he didn't, but he just laughed and told me:
"Don't use bacon from tha' pork, use Bresaola"
If you are looking for the "perfect" carbonara and you'd like to test out something new, why not testing this?
Have a good day :)

textDisplay: Hi there, I have been making spaghetti carbonara for a number of years, but I too do not just make this one as an original, I made a chicken one, with some fresh chicken fillets, I had been kindly given, I then wanted to use up last few bits of veggies I had, rather than make a veggie soup...So I made chicken and leek with mushrooms and asparagus oh and cauliflower...But Same way with the raw eggs and plenty of pepper, so I have enough for two meals now. I also do not eat gluten, so I made used gluten free with Quinoa, less cooking time, but turned out great and no heavy bloated feeling or uncomfortableness after..Enjoy ..whether you make original or play with your own leftover ingredients

textDisplay:
I am Italian and pasta carbonara is one of my favorite dishes.
In this video the chef made three serious mistakes: first of all.. the egg white is not put in the real carbonara but only the yolk!!, second mistake the garlic is not adeed and finally the cooking water salt water should be addedonly in small quantities otherwise the pasta will be too salty! (the salt is already present both in the pecorino cheese and also in the guanciale)
textOriginal:

textDisplay:
I’m Italian.
Carbonara is a relatively recent recipe invented in Rome after the US Army entered in the town after WW2. Eggs and bacon was ingredents familiar to GIs’ taste so a restaurant started mixing them to make a pasta dish they could appreciate. Thus there’s no “classic carbonara recipe”. As a matter of fact in its first version it was probably made with bacon and egg powder from the Army rations so guanciale was used later.
All that said one thing is for sure:
you can use either guanciale or psncetta or bacon, you can even add a little cream but....
NOBODY in Italy would ever put garlic in carbonara!!! NO GARLIC IN CARBONARA!
textOriginal:
I’m Italian. 
Carbonara is a relatively recent recipe invented in Rome after the US Army entered in the town after WW2. Eggs and bacon was ingredents familiar to GIs’ taste so a restaurant started mixing them to make a pasta dish they could appreciate. Thus there’s no “classic carbonara recipe”. As a matter of fact in its first version it was probably made with bacon and egg powder from the Army rations so guanciale was used later.
All that said one thing is for sure:
you can use either guanciale or psncetta or bacon, you can even add a little cream but....
NOBODY in Italy would ever put garlic in carbonara!!! NO GARLIC IN CARBONARA!

textDisplay:
Fosse così semplice, ma agli italiani piace accapigliarsi.
Quale pasta? Spaghetti n.5? Ma c'è chi preferisce gli spaghettoni, chi i bucatini (che però sono una gran rottura se cerchi di risucchiarli).
Il guanciale, tagliato come? A listine, a dadini, a striscioline? Eeeeeè fondamentale, dai!
L'uovo, di gallina padovana o livornese? Guscio chiaro come nel video o scuro? E un albume ce lo metti oppure no?
Il pepe, macinato o pestato? Pepe delle isole della Sonda o pepe di Zanzibar?
Infine, hai dimenticato l'acqua! L'acqua è fondamentale: quale residuo fisso deve avere l'acqua? Si può fare la carbonara con l'acqua leggera delle Alpi o ci vuole necessariamente l'acqua mineralizzata del centro Italia? E il sale, sale marino o salgemma?
E se poi ti venisse voglia di una carbonara ma non avessi il guanciale, non dire in giro che hai usato la pancetta perché i custodi dell'ortodossia potrebbero lapidarti sulla pubblica piazza, occhio!
textOriginal:
Fosse così semplice, ma agli italiani piace accapigliarsi.
Quale pasta? Spaghetti n.5? Ma c'è chi preferisce gli spaghettoni, chi i bucatini (che però sono una gran rottura se cerchi di risucchiarli).
Il guanciale, tagliato come? A listine, a dadini, a striscioline? Eeeeeè fondamentale, dai!
L'uovo, di gallina padovana o livornese? Guscio chiaro come nel video o scuro? E un albume ce lo metti oppure no?
Il pepe, macinato o pestato? Pepe delle isole della Sonda o pepe di Zanzibar?
Infine, hai dimenticato l'acqua! L'acqua è fondamentale: quale residuo fisso deve avere l'acqua? Si può fare la carbonara con l'acqua leggera delle Alpi o ci vuole necessariamente l'acqua mineralizzata del centro Italia? E il sale, sale marino o salgemma?
E se poi ti venisse voglia di una carbonara ma non avessi il guanciale, non dire in giro che hai usato la pancetta perché i custodi dell'ortodossia potrebbero lapidarti sulla pubblica piazza, occhio!

textDisplay: The cream is actually created from the water emulsifying with the cheese. Adding heavy or whipping cream is technically the same thing (All dairy products) but it doesn't taste as good and dilutes the rich, salty, aged cheese flavor; it's like adding olive oil to EVOO. People only add cream to save on cost in a restaurant but it's a pointless ingredient when cooking for yourself.

textDisplay:
I moved out of home with 0 cooking skills and the way I started teaching myself is by going really basic and oldschool. Like 19th century poor peasant food-oldschool. If I can't make sour soup (water, sour cream, caraway seeds, potatoes) taste alright then I probably won't manage beef wellington. I feel like that approach served me right, I started buying better ingredients once I knew what I was doing. No need to buy a 50$ chunk of meat if I am going to cook it to death, in my mind technique is more important than food quality (up to a point). Plus I now have a decent repertoire of delicious and cheap food built up which is always nice.


The most important thing I've learned is to just taste everything all the time. If your food comes out bland you didn't taste it enough else you would have adjusted.
textOriginal:
I moved out of home with 0 cooking skills and the way I started teaching myself is by going really basic and oldschool. Like 19th century poor peasant food-oldschool. If I can't make sour soup (water, sour cream, caraway seeds, potatoes) taste alright then I probably won't manage beef wellington. I feel like that approach served me right, I started buying better ingredients once I knew what I was doing. No need to buy a 50$ chunk of meat if I am going to cook it to death, in my mind technique is more important than food quality (up to a point). Plus I now have a decent repertoire of delicious and cheap food built up which is always nice.


The most important thing I've learned is to just taste everything all the time. If your food comes out bland you didn't taste it enough else you would have adjusted.
